From b4a0a5a238fecc280781e6fe5719faf0eafcd667 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nakata Maho <maho.nakata@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 2026 10:11:15 +0900
Subject: [PATCH] M35: add level-sensitive IRQ acknowledge support

---
 README.md                         |  19 +
 test/Makefile                     |  10 +
 test/test-interrupt-extension.cpp | 558 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 z80.hpp                           |  58 +++-
 4 files changed, 638 insertions(+), 7 deletions(-)
 create mode 100644 test/test-interrupt-extension.cpp

diff --git a/README.md b/README.md
index d8f0e39..c5945ad 100644
--- a/README.md
+++ b/README.md
@@ -224,6 +224,25 @@ actualExecuteClocks = 19Hz ... 2147483647Hz+ is not executed but interrupted aft
     z80.generateIRQ(vector);
 ```
 
+Existing code that only calls `generateIRQ` keeps its one-shot request and
+vector semantics. For a level-sensitive interrupt source, install an
+acknowledge callback and drive the IRQ line explicitly:
+
+```c++
+    z80.setInterruptAcknowledgeCallback([](void* arg) -> unsigned char {
+        Device* device = static_cast<Device*>(arg);
+        return device->acknowledgeIRQ();
+    });
+    z80.setIRQLine(true);  // assertion persists across acceptance
+    z80.setIRQLine(false); // deassert when the source is no longer active
+```
+
+The callback runs once when a maskable interrupt is accepted, not when the
+line is asserted. Its byte is the raw first opcode in IM0, is ignored in IM1,
+and is the vector low byte in IM2. Use `isIRQLineAsserted` to inspect the line
+state and `setIRQLine` to restore it. Function-pointer versions of the callback
+API are available when building with `Z80_NO_FUNCTIONAL`.
+
 #### NMI; Non Maskable Interrupt
 
 ```c++
